The operational objective is to maximize the number of concurrent task execution assignments. Strict business rules mandate that, at any given time, each incoming computational task may be assigned to at most one server, and each server may receive at most one incoming computational task. Furthermore, all scheduling assignments must be confined exclusively to the aforementioned 15 feasible compatibility paths.

Formulate a scheduling scheme that maximizes the number of successfully matched task–server pairs while satisfying all stated constraints.

An e-commerce fulfillment center is optimizing its assignment system for orders containing specific hazardous materials. The facility processes six distinct orders containing hazardous materials (indexed 0 to 5) and operates five packing stations certified and equipped to handle those material classes (indexed 0 to 4). Due to strict safety regulations regarding certification compatibility between order material classes and packing station equipment, not every order can be routed to every station. There are exactly 11 predefined feasible connection paths where an order's material class matches a station's certification, specified as follows:
- Order 0 can be assigned to Packing Station 0, Packing Station 1, or Packing Station 4;
- Order 1 can be assigned to Packing Station 2;
- Order 2 can be assigned to Packing Station 0, Packing Station 1, or Packing Station 4;
- Order 3 can be assigned to Packing Station 0, Packing Station 1, or Packing Station 2;
- Order 4 can be assigned to Packing Station 3;
- Order 5 has no compatible packing stations based on current certifications.

The operational objective is to maximize the number of concurrent order fulfillment assignments. Strict business rules mandate that, at any given time, each order containing hazardous materials may be routed to at most one packing station, and each packing station may process at most one order. Furthermore, all scheduling assignments must be confined exclusively to the aforementioned 11 feasible connection paths defined by the certification compatibility.

Formulate an assignment scheme that maximizes the number of successfully matched order–station pairs while satisfying all stated constraints.

An automotive manufacturer operates a rigid automated assembly line dedicated to multi-model vehicle production. The facility has received an urgent order requiring the assembly of four distinct vehicle production orders, designated V0 through V3. To complete the assembly of these vehicles, all units must strictly adhere to an identical assembly sequence path, sequentially passing through three critical assembly workstations: W0, W1, and W2. Due to the facility's rigid automotive assembly line design, once the input sequence of vehicles at the first assembly workstation (W0) is determined, all subsequent workstations must strictly follow this same vehicle sequencing; reordering between workstations is not permitted.

Based on current process parameters, the assembly durations (in minutes) for each vehicle production order at the respective workstations are as follows:
- Vehicle V0: 47 minutes at W0, 11 minutes at W1, and 33 minutes at W2;
- Vehicle V1: 13 minutes at W0, 15 minutes at W1, and 48 minutes at W2;
- Vehicle V2: 47 minutes at W0, 12 minutes at W1, and 46 minutes at W2;
- Vehicle V3: 50 minutes at W0, 20 minutes at W1, and 49 minutes at W2.

The production scheduling problem is subject to strict physical constraints: at any given time, each assembly workstation can handle only one vehicle, and each vehicle can be processed at only one workstation simultaneously. Parallel processing or preemption is strictly prohibited. The plant manager's objective is to devise an optimal vehicle sequencing scheme that minimizes the total line completion time—defined as the time elapsed from the entry of the first vehicle into workstation W0 until the completion and exit of the last vehicle from workstation W2—thereby enabling the fastest possible order fulfillment.

